<!-- Async WordPress.com Remote Login -->
<script id="wpcom_remote_login_js">
var wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth = '';
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( element_id ) {
	var dom_node = document.getElementById( element_id );
	if ( dom_node ) { dom_node.remove(); }
}
function wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( class_name ) {
	var dom_nodes = document.querySelectorAll( '.' + class_name );
	for ( var i = 0; i < dom_nodes.length; i++ ) {
		dom_nodes[i].remove();
	}
}
function wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup() {
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_classes( "wpcom_remote_login_msg" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_js" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_iframe" );
	wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_request_access_styles" );
}

// Watch for messages back from the remote login
window.addEventListener( "message", function( e ) {
	if ( e.origin === "https://r-login.wordpress.com" ) {
		var data = {};
		try {
			data = JSON.parse( e.data );
		} catch( e ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
			return;
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN' ) {
			// Clean up the login check iframe
			wpcom_remote_login_remove_dom_node_id( "wpcom_remote_login_key" );

			var id_regex = new RegExp( /^[0-9]+$/ );
			var token_regex = new RegExp( /^.*|.*|.*$/ );
			if (
				token_regex.test( data.token )
				&& id_regex.test( data.wpcomid )
			) {
				// We have everything we need to ask for a login
				var script = document.createElement( "script" );
				script.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_validate" );
				script.src = '/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=validate'
					+ '&wpcomid=' + data.wpcomid
					+ '&token=' + encodeURIComponent( data.token )
					+ '&host=' + window.location.protocol
						+ '//' + window.location.hostname;
				document.body.appendChild( script );
			}

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, not logged in, so redirect
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REDIRECT' ) {
			window.location = 'https://wordpress.com/log-in?redirect_to=' + window.location.href;
			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP, storage access failed, remove the request
		if ( data.msg === 'LOGIN-REMOVE' ) {
			var css_zap = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 782px ) { html { margin-top: 0 !important; } * html body { margin-top: 0 !important; } }';
			var style_zap = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style_zap.type = 'text/css';
			style_zap.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css_zap ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style_zap );

			var e = document.getElementById( 'wpcom_request_access_iframe' );
			e.parentNode.removeChild( e );

			document.cookie = 'wordpress_com_login_access=denied; path=/; max-age=31536000';

			return;
		}

		// Safari ITP
		if ( data.msg === 'REQUEST_ACCESS' ) {
			console.log( 'request access: safari' );

			// Check ITP iframe enable/disable knob
			if ( wpcom_remote_login_extra_auth !== 'safari_itp_iframe' ) {
				return;
			}

			// If we are in a "private window" there is no ITP.
			var private_window = false;
			try {
				var opendb = window.openDatabase( null, null, null, null );
			} catch( e ) {
				private_window = true;
			}

			if ( private_window ) {
				console.log( 'private window' );
				return;
			}

			var iframe = document.createElement( 'iframe' );
			iframe.id = 'wpcom_request_access_iframe';
			iframe.setAttribute( 'scrolling', 'no' );
			iframe.setAttribute( 'sandbox', 'allow-storage-access-by-user-activation allow-scripts allow-same-origin allow-top-navigation-by-user-activation' );
			iframe.src = 'https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php?wpcom_remote_login=request_access&origin=' + encodeURIComponent( data.origin ) + '&wpcomid=' + encodeURIComponent( data.wpcomid );

			var css = 'html { -webkit-transition: margin-top 1s; transition: margin-top 1s; } /* 9001 */ html { margin-top: 46px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 46px !important; } @media screen and ( max-width: 660px ) { html { margin-top: 71px !important; } * html body { margin-top: 71px !important; } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { display: block; height: 71px !important; } } #wpcom_request_access_iframe { border: 0px; height: 46px; position: fixed; top: 0; left: 0; width: 100%; min-width: 100%; z-index: 99999; background: #23282d; } ';

			var style = document.createElement( 'style' );
			style.type = 'text/css';
			style.id = 'wpcom_request_access_styles';
			style.appendChild( document.createTextNode( css ) );
			document.body.appendChild( style );

			document.body.appendChild( iframe );
		}

		if ( data.msg === 'DONE' ) {
			wpcom_remote_login_final_cleanup();
		}
	}
}, false );

// Inject the remote login iframe after the page has had a chance to load
// more critical resources
window.addEventListener( "DOMContentLoaded", function( e ) {
	var iframe = document.createElement( "iframe" );
	iframe.style.display = "none";
	iframe.setAttribute( "scrolling", "no" );
	iframe.setAttribute( "id", "wpcom_remote_login_key" );
	iframe.src = "https://r-login.wordpress.com/remote-login.php"
		+ "?wpcom_remote_login=key"
		+ "&origin=aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGFja2xpc3RkZWNsYXNzaWZpZWQubmV0"
		+ "&wpcomid=9473618"
		+ "&time=1603821809";
	document.body.appendChild( iframe );
}, false );
</script>

		function addLoadEvent(func) {
			var oldonload = window.onload;
			if (typeof window.onload != 'function') {
				window.onload = func;
			} else {
				window.onload = function () {
					oldonload();
					func();
				}
			}
		}

				<h3 class="entry-title"><a href="https://blacklistdeclassified.net/2012/03/03/%f0%9f%94%b4-easy-search-s3-scripts/" rel="bookmark">üî¥ Easy-Search S3 Scripts&nbsp;‚¨ÖÔ∏è</a></h3>

<h2>üî¥ Episode 3:1 The Troll Farmer</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Last updated: 10/5/2015 7:10am CT, Program air date: 10/1/2015 in the US<br />
Script Status = <b><i>Final</i></b> w music lyrics, Twitter photos<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-1Iy" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-1Iy</a><br />
Storybook: <a href="http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#troll" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#troll</a><br />
Source: Raw Scripts from Springfield [UK]: <a href="http://bit.ly/1VtXhJ6" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1VtXhJ6</a> (dump of captioning)<br />
<b>WSJ Episode Summary:</b> <a href="http://on.wsj.com/1LY4cov" rel="nofollow">http://on.wsj.com/1LY4cov</a><br />
&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb:</b> Accused of having killed the Attorney General (which she did) and of being a Russian spy, (which she is not), Liz goes underground with Red. Liz changes her hair color to blonde, stirring in Red memories of her mother, the notorious Katarina Rostova.</i><br />

<b>Red:</b> [ Chuckles, walks away, trying to regain his composure ] The Troll Farmer uses social media to conduct highly coordinated disinformation campaigns on behalf of governments, lobbyists, corporations, crime syndicates, and on occasion, a humble fugitive. He&#8217;s mastered the art of information warfare by creating events, virtual hoaxes designed to piggyback on real public anxiety. He activates hundreds of fake accounts to post thousands of tweets, creating the appearance of, say, a terrorist attack in Paris that served as cover for an art heist. He doctors screenshots from news outlets to report an ebola outbreak in Atlanta in order to drive up the stock of a drug company developing a cure. The Troll Farmer is much more than a rumor monger. The events he creates appear to be real and provoke a very real response. Smoke manufactured to draw the cameras away from the real fire.‚ô§<br />

<b>Red:</b>  Marvin Gerard was one of the most respected defense attorneys on the Eastern seaboard. Perfect wife, perfect job, perfect, all of it. Save for his son Timothy. Quiet boy. Fell in with some bad eggs, it seems. Disciplinary issues, troubles at school, drug abuse. Timothy was getting a steady supply of amphetamines from his mother&#8217;s shrink‚Äì Ritalin, Adderall. She constantly bullied the boy. Marvin and his wife separated. He fought for custody, contacted police, social services. But his wife was the princess in a very prominent and powerful legal dynasty, so no action was ever taken. Timothy remained in her sole custody. Her abuse worsened. Convinced he had no other option, Marvin kidnapped the boy. They tracked him down, of course. Returned the child to his mother. Marvin was disbarred, convicted, and incarcerated.<br />
Liz: And what happened to his son?<br />
<b>Red:</b>  A year later, Timothy hung himself. He was 15.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Agent: Snipers in position for cover. Teams make simultaneous entries here and here. Flashbangs and smoke. Secure and contain the scenario. Counter minimal risk of collateral damage. We&#8217;re all set on my mark.<br />

<p>Ressler: Forget it.<br />

<b>Red:</b> The Director needed permission to have me killed. And he only got it by convincing others that I didn&#8217;t have the Fulcrum. That was a costly mistake. <p>&nbsp;<br />

<b>Red:</b> They&#8217;re the world&#8217;s largest agribusiness. They sell seeds. More to the point, genetically engineered seeds. In fact, they&#8217;re the single largest manufacturer of genetically engineered seeds on Earth, and not just any seeds. Corn, soy, the crops at the very foundation of our food economy.<br />
Liz: I&#8217;ve read about this. Modifying the DNA of the seed itself, teaching it to create a protein that kills common pests that would eat it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, and those seeds are very expensive. Most small farmers can&#8217;t afford them. Many of them have been driven out of business. And when people feel their homes and livelihoods threatened, violence is never far behind. A few days ago, a Verdiant facility was attacked by a group of small farmers who call themselves Los Segadores [ &#8220;The Harvesters&#8221; ], men determined to kill Verdiant before it kills them.<br />
Liz: Damaging one building will hardly kill Verdiant.<br />
<b>Red:</b> They did more than damage a building, Lizzy. They stole data, a cache of proprietary files detailing how Verdiant modifies its corn genome. That&#8217;s a trade secret worth billions of dollars. You and I are gonna take those files from the men who stole them.<br />
Liz: Assuming we could do that, why would we?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Verdiant launders money for the Cabal. Hundreds of millions of dollars a year. If we get those files, we have leverage over Verdiant. We have leverage over Verdiant, we have leverage over the Cabal.</p>

Cooper: You know what? You&#8217;re right. You should trust your gut, not mine. After all, look where my instincts got me. You&#8217;re a good agent, Donald. You made the right call.</p>

You sign off. The Djinn verifies your financial resources. If she likes what she sees, she contacts you directly to set a meeting.<br />

Aram: It is decentralized, cached on servers all over the world. I take one down, two pop up.<br />
It is completely anonymous, so there&#8217;s no way to tell who this Arioch Cain really is. When NYPD forwarded me the hard drive, they told me they believe there&#8217;s a laptop that&#8217;s missing.<br />

Aram: Haters ‚Äì people who believe what they read about Agent Keen. They make Bitcoin donations ‚Äì the miracle of crowdsourcing turned on its head to crowd-fund murder. The more notorious the target, the bigger the fund, and the more people who will try it. We thought Wendigo was bad. This is way worse. There&#8217;s no limit to how many assassins could be coming after her.</p>

<p><a id="peach"></a></p>
<blockquote><p>
&nbsp;<br />
<b>Meaning of &#8220;Do I dare to eat a peach?&#8221; üçë</b></p>
<p>Last Stanzas of &#8220;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock&#8221;<br />
by T.S. Eliot (1920)</p>
<p>&#8220;I grow old ‚Ä¶ I grow old ‚Ä¶<br />
I shall wear the bottoms of my trousers rolled.	</p>
<p>Shall I part my hair behind? <b><i>Do I dare to eat a peach?</i></b><br />
I shall wear white flannel trousers, and walk upon the beach.<br />
I have heard the mermaids singing, each to each.	</p>
<p>I do not think that they will sing to me.</p>
<p>I have seen them riding seaward on the waves<br />
Combing the white hair of the waves blown back<br />
When the wind blows the water white and black.	</p>
<p>We have lingered in the chambers of the sea<br />
By sea-girls wreathed with seaweed red and brown<br />
Till human voices wake us, and we drown.&#8221;</p>
<p>Source: Bartleby[.]com: <a href="http://bit.ly/1Ybcdis" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1Ybcdis</a></p>
<p>‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ‚îÅ </p>
<p><b><i>An Interpretation</i></b> (not atypical):<br />
&#8220;While Eliot&#8217;s main intent is to trivialize Prufrock&#8217;s anxieties ‚Äì a simple piece of fruit confounds him ‚Äì the peach has a few other possible meanings. First, it is the Chinese symbol for marriage and immortality, two things Prufrock desires. Moreover, the peach, through shape and texture, has long been a symbol for female genitalia. Prufrock&#8217;s anxiety about eating a peach, then, has much to do with his feelings of sexual inadequacy, his worry that his balding head and thin physique earn him the scorn of women.&#8221;<br />
Wayne, Teddy. <i>&#8220;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock Study Guide&#8221;</i> 13 August 2002 <a href="http://bit.ly/1QnUQtm" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1QnUQtm</a> (Bio: Novelist, Harvard educated, contributor to The New Yorker, eg Oct 2015 <a href="http://bit.ly/1OKvnu5" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1OKvnu5</a>)</p>
<p><b><i>Other Sources: </i></b><br />
‚óè BritLitWiki: <i>Imagery in &#8220;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock&#8221;</i> <a href="http://bit.ly/1HJMc5R" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1HJMc5R</a><br />
‚óè JEduSci (2008): <i>Objective Correlative in Eliot&#8217;s &#8220;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock&#8221;</i> <a href="http://bit.ly/1WSiylK" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1WSiylK</a> pp 7,10<br />
‚óè NYSciJ (1988): <i>T. S. Eliot&#8217;s Tragic Strategy in: &#8220;The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock&#8221;</i>  <a href="http://bit.ly/1YaQ5Vj" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1YaQ5Vj</a> pp 113-114<br />
‚ûî  Or ‚Ä¶ Google it.</p>
<p><b>Notably,</b> Red <u>does</u> drink the peach juice, saying, &#8220;I may as well live dangerously.&#8221;
</p></blockquote>

As for consumption, I must admit to a fondness for any well-appointed opium den, and a bit of hashish goes well with just about anything. But stimulants, I have no taste for. I prefer that slight curve at the small of the back, the swell of a breast, the soft nape of the neck to quicken my heartbeat.‚ô§<br />

Especially in England. The wealthy Brits? They are cocaine mad over there. Go figure. Why don&#8217;t you grab some kilos off the top and let&#8217;s go stage a crime scene? </p>

<h2>üî¥ Episode 3:10 The Director, Part 2</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Last updated: 1/17/2016 2:00pm CT, Program air date: 1/14/2016 in the US<br />
Script Status: <b><i>Final</b></i><br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-2k0" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-2k0</a><br />
<b>Storybook:</b> <a href="http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#director2" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#director2</a><i> (2-3 days after script is done)</i><br />
Source: Raw Scripts from Springfield [UK]: <a href="http://bit.ly/1VtXhJ6" rel="nofollow">http://bit.ly/1VtXhJ6</a> (captions)<br />
<b>WSJ Episode Summary:</b> <a href="http://on.wsj.com/1PfZjsD" rel="nofollow">http://on.wsj.com/1PfZjsD</a><br />
&nbsp;<br />
<i><b>Blurb: </b>Red and lawyer Marvin Gerard have a plan to exonerate Elizabeth Keen. Red gathers his troops and leaves Ressler in charge of guarding Keen. The Cabal has plans of its own.</i><br />

<p><b>Red:</b> Hello, Harold. You look pretty well, considering. Thank you all for coming. I apologize for the security protocols, but my better half insists. Just the fact that you are all here is a testament to the deep concern we share for Elizabeth Keen&#8217;s safety and well-being.<br />
üî∫ The threat from forces within is proving to be more powerful and far-reaching than one could ever have imagined. I&#8217;ve asked you here because we have one chance to save Elizabeth. But to do that, we must work together.<br />
üî∫ So [ Laughs ] Oh, my God, this is why I&#8217;m a terrible bridge player. With anyone else, Steve Lyditt would have won the North American pairs. We didn&#8217;t even make it through regionals. I abhor working with a partner. Sharing my hand with anyone goes against every instinct I have. ‚ô§<br />
üî∫ But such is life. Here we are.<br />
üî∫ So, five weeks ago, I called the Metro PD to report a sighting of Raymond Reddington at the Del Rio diner. I created a hostage crisis so you would be so kind as to release my attorney, Marvin Gerard, from prison. That day, Marvin and I conceived a plan to exonerate Elizabeth Keen by targeting the Cabal, and, in particular, the Director. Since that day, everything we&#8217;ve done has been in service of that plan.<br />
üî∫ The Verdiant case has resulted in catastrophic damage to the Cabal&#8217;s finances. The client list we took from The Djinn gave us leverage with key players in the Cabal to further isolate and weaken the Director&#8217;s influence. With Andras Halmi, or part of him, we cut a gaping hole ‚Äì in the Director&#8217;s golden parachute ‚Äì [ Beep, whir ] leaving him nothing to run with and causing even further distrust and divisions within the Cabal.<br />
üî∫ But the Zal Bin Haasan case has opened a window of opportunity we must slip through with great haste. To save Elizabeth, we must execute a specific attack, one so impactful, it will force the Cabal to completely abandon the Director and publicly exonerate Elizabeth Keen.<br />
Cooper: What the hell do you have in mind?<br />
<b>Red:</b> See, this is why I don&#8217;t play well with partners. Don&#8217;t fret, Harold. I&#8217;m holding all the trumps. I&#8217;ll be the declarer, you be the dummy, and we&#8217;ll win the hand. Anything else? Good. Let&#8217;s begin.</p>

<p>‚ô™  <i>I&#8217;ll rise up in spite of the ache I rise up </i> </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: You&#8217;re sure about this?<br />
Ressler: I haven&#8217;t been sure about much lately, but, yeah, this one I know. I&#8217;m a field agent. I kick down doors. I&#8217;ll leave all the politics and bureaucracy to the pros.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;m proud of you, Agent Ressler. You&#8217;re the agent I always aspired to be.<br />
Ressler: [ Chuckles ] Welcome back, sir. You know what gets me? Laurel Hitchin just walks away unscathed.<br />
Cooper: That&#8217;s a fight for another day.</p>
<p><i> ‚ô™ feels like it&#8217;s getting hard to breathe<br />
and I know you feel like dying </i></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Hitchin: I don&#8217;t know why you want this. The organization&#8217;s in disarray. Weaker than it&#8217;s ever been. It occurred to me that maybe this was always part of your endgame ‚Äì to tear us down so you could build us up and have a seat at the table.<br />
[ The person Hitchin is talking to is Red ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ ‚Ä¶ rise like the day<br />
I&#8217;ll rise up<br />
in spite of the ache<br />
I will rise a thousand times again
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ The music grows louder. It&#8217;s nightime when Liz is released. She is escorted through the marbled halls of the almost empty Court House to freedom. She walks down the long marble staircase to the sidewalk below. Liz looks around. Few souls are awake. Liz is alone in the dark. A bus goes by. When it has passed, she sees Red across the street. His face is serene, benevolent. Liz gasps her surprise, then smiles, runs across the street to him, pauses, then throws her arms around his neck. He gathers her against himself and strokes her tangled hair. ]</p>

<b>Red:</b>  Your past three months have been what my life has been like for the past 25 years. I&#8217;m often exhausted. The Shell Island retreat is a ritual that dates back to the roaring &#8217;20s. The de facto master of ceremonies is Marcus Caligiuri, next in line to Espen Van Der Merwe, but to assume leadership in the Pater Dei group, the world&#8217;s oldest and largest weapons dealer. The leaders of the Bratva, Yakuza, and assorted international cartels. They gather when they are presented with a problem so difficult, it can only be resolved by enemies working together.<br />
Liz: And where is this Shell Island?<br />
<b>Red:</b>  There is no Shell Island. It&#8217;s just a name. The actual location of the meeting is always a closely guarded secret.<br />

<b>Red:</b>  Howard Jasnoch. He&#8217;s a competitor of mine. He&#8217;s arranged transport for the individual who called the meeting.<br />
Liz: And who is that?<br />
<b>Red:</b>  I don&#8217;t know. What I do know is if he&#8217;s called a meeting and the members are gathering, he&#8217;s a very big fish. Whatever is troubling him, whatever has caught the attention of these men is critical. No less than an existential threat. These meetings are infrequent, Lizzy, making this a very rare opportunity. Follow this fish, and you can net the entire school. </p>

You have given false allegations against my good name, which will be whispered and repeated by those who envy my success no matter how thoroughly I repudiate them.<br />

[ Thudding, clatter ] [ Someone cracks open a cuff link, revealing the wire ] [ Radio static whines ] [ Helicopter blades whirring ]<br />

[ Gun cocks ] [ Grunting ] [ Sound of helicopters ]<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />

<h2>üî¥ Episode 3:15 Drexel</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
NBC&#8217;s series <b>The Blacklist</b> starring <b>James Spader</b> and <b>Megan Boone</b><br />
<b>Series created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b><br />
Program air date: 2/18//2016 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-2w7" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-2w7</a> ¬§ Storybook: <a href="http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#drexel" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#drexel</a></p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb:</b> Technology and artistic expression come together with murderous results. Tom hovers near death and Liz suspects Red.</p></blockquote>
</blockquote>

<b>Red:</b> Because Roberta Smith at the Times said it was worth a look. And it seemed like a fitting spot to introduce our next adventure. You&#8217;re looking at a crime-scene photo. It appeared online a few hours ago, along with a breaking-news bulletin about the murder of Randy Brenner at his new home in Richmond. The local police are flummoxed. It obviously wasn&#8217;t your typical home invasion or burglary gone wrong. It wasn&#8217;t a crime of passion. It is, in fact, to one somewhat disturbed individual, quite literally a work of art. Those who know of his existence call him Drexel. Considers himself a performance artist. And like most performance artists, his work is a form of social commentary.<br />
Liz: Most performance artists don&#8217;t kill people in service of their work.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Last winter, he murdered the owner of one of the largest CAFOs in Europe.<br />
Liz: CAFO?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A Controlled Animal Feeding Operation. Hung the owner up on a hook like the cattle they butcher.<br />
Liz: A little heavy-handed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Laughs ] Drexel does not employ subtlety to get his point across. His work shows up in unexpected locations&#8230; sometimes only for a few hours.<br />
Liz: This man has fans? People support him?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. A small-but-rabid following. Death as entertainment. Drexel makes them feel part of something‚Äì an underground protest movement.<br />
Liz: And how do you know Drexel killed Randy Brenner?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Because he&#8217;s advertising it. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

From what I can tell, it uses artificial intelligence to modify its payload, which is rare. Like, super-rare. In fact, I&#8217;ve seen this exact AI automation before‚Äì once. As part of a classified security briefing by the NSA.<br />

Ressler: So, what? What, this was like a political statement?<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Guard: As far as you go, pops. Whatever you&#8217;re looking for, this ain&#8217;t it.<br />

[ Dembe goes at him, pins him to the wall ]<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Camera shutter clicks ]<br />
Emilio: Wow. Raymond Reddington. I mean, you&#8217;re actually him.<br />

<h2>üî¥ Episode 3:17 Mr Solomon</h2>

The heart rate is plummeting. If I don&#8217;t perform an emergency C-section in the next 10 minutes, her baby&#8217;s going to die. </p>

<h2>üî¥ Script: 3:19 Cape May</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
NBC&#8217;s series <b>The Blacklist</b> starring <b>James Spader</b> and <b>Megan Boone</b><br />
<b>Series created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b><br />
Program air date: 4/21/2016 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-2RN" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-2RN</a></p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb:</b> Grieving over the tragic death of Lizzie, Red is drawn to Cape May where he must come to terms with the past.
</p></blockquote>

<h3>üî¥ Script 3:19 Cape May</h3>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is interrogating Nik, Liz&#8217;s ER doctor (and her ex-boyfriend). Nik tried to save Liz&#8217;s life but failed. The interrogation room is the same as the one Red used in 3:12 The Vehm to execute the man who had attacked Liz in a supermarket parking lot ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Nik: Given her abrupt drop in blood pressure and pulse, I diagnosed a placental abruption. We performed a successful emergency C-section. She was having chest pains, shortness of breath&#8230; classic symptoms of an amniotic fluid embolism. Her lungs were no longer functioning. I had to get her to a trauma unit. We were losing her. And she went into arrest.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s enough.<br />
Nik: I kept her alive long enough to become a mother.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What a desperate thing to say.<br />
Nik: I don&#8217;t want to die.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Everyone dies someday. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ INDISTINCT TALKING ]<br />
[ An elderly Chinese woman opens a secret wall in a restaurant and descends the stairs to an opium den. Red is sleeping fully clothed on a thin mattress recessed into the wall ]<br />
Elderly Chinese woman: Time to go, Mr. Red. Time to go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Mumbling ] No. No, no, not yet. I want another one. I want another one. I paid and I want another.<br />
Chinese woman: No. You go. It&#8217;s Friday. It&#8217;s too long for you. You go.<br />
[ GROANS ] [ COUGHS ] [ COUGHS LOUDLY ]<br />
[ Red gets up and heads out, leaving behind his pistol and fedora ]<br />
Chinese woman: [ Calling him back: ] Mr. Red.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Mm.<br />
[ Red turns back and takes his hat but not the gun ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red seems to be in a stupor ] [ TIRES SCREECH, HORN HONKS as a car almost hits Red. The car has a sign &#8220;Taxi 4 hire&#8221; in the window.&#8221; The car has New York plates ]<br />
Cabbie: [ Rolls down window and calls out ] You trying to get yourself killed?<br />
[ Red gets in the cab ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Cape May. Cape May, New Jersey.<br />
Cabbie: That&#8217;s 200 miles away.<br />
[ Red counts out five $100 bills ]<br />
Cabbie: Cape May it is.</p>
<blockquote><p>
[ Flashbacks: ]<br />
[ MONITOR FLATLINES ] [ GASPS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Don&#8217;t go, Lizzy. Please, don&#8217;t go.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ BABY COOS ]<br />
Tom: Now go. And stay away from us.
</p></blockquote>
<p><b>Red:</b> Everyone dies someday.<br />
Cabbie: You say something? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Electric razor buzzes as Red shaves while leaving a message for his lawyer, Marvin Gerard ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Marvin, it&#8217;s Raymond. I&#8217;m taking a leave of indeterminate length. Suspend all transactions. Pay off all my outstanding debt. If you need additional funds to cover any shortfall, execute a wire transfer from Barbados. Dembe has a power of attorney letter on file should a signature be necessary.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ To the cabbie ] How much for the cab?<br />
Cabbie: No, you&#8217;re good.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, no. How much do you want for the cab?<br />
Cabbie: You&#8217;re kidding, right?<br />
[ Red plops many thick stacks of bills on the car hood, hundreds of thousands of dollars, maybe millions ]<br />
Cabbie: That&#8217;s plenty. Thank you. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red stops for breakfast at a greasy spoon, orders bacon and eggs. He notices a woman seated in a booth by the window. She sees something and hurries out. A man comes into the restaurant and uses the rotary dial pay phone ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red arrives at an inn just behind the sand dunes. It is closed for the season. He pushes through the gate ]<br />
[ DOOR OPENS ] [ KNOCK ON DOOR ] [ WIND CHIMES TINKLING ] [ DOOR OPENS ]  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The beach at Cape May is deserted. Red takes a folding lounge chair and opens it on the beach. He looks out to sea. The day is dull and cold. Red suddenly sees the same red-haired woman from the restaurant sitting on the beach. She takes off her coat and a necklace and walks into the water a ways, then dives in ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hey! Hey! No! Stop!<br />
[ Red runs, shedding his coat, suitcoat and hat along the way, then runs into the 40 degree water, looking for the woman. A large wave tumbles over him. He rescues the mysterious woman and drags her onto the beach ]<br />
[ CRIES ] [ COUGHS ] [ COUGHING ] [ GASPING ] [ GRUNTS ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red helps the woman walk to the white inn building, into an apartment, and helps her down onto a rug on the floor in front of a fireplace. He covers her with a sheet and places two decorator pillows under her head ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;ll find a blanket. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ BELL DINGS ]<br />
Woman behind desk: May I help you?<br />
[ Red has just taken a blanket and some matches from a closet in the lobby. He turns around. The woman is gone ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ BREATHES HEAVILY ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red starts a fire in the fireplace, then he lies down on the floor next to the woman, pulling the blanket over both of them and cradling her head on his arm, his other arm pulling her close to him ]<br />
Red. You&#8217;re okay. Talk to me.<br />
Woman: [ In a whisper ] It&#8217;s not that he died. It&#8217;s not even the way he died. It&#8217;s in the things I said to him&#8230; just before he died.  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red wakes. It&#8217;s lighter outside. Red is alone on the floor. He is wearing a tee-shirt and shorts. He pulls his pants on and climbs the stairs. He finds the woman peering out of a window ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hello? You okay?<br />
Woman: [ GASPS ] There&#8217;s someone here. Outside. He&#8217;s here to kill me. There. There he is. See his shadow?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Stay away from the window.<br />
[ Red grabs an ax and heads outdoors ]<br />
[ ROCKING CHAIR CREAKING, WIND CHIMES TINKLING ] [ GRUNTS ] [ GASPS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I found the intruder. He put up a fight. I had no choice but to kill him. [ He has a torn black kite ]<br />
Woman: You must think I&#8217;m crazy.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red comes to the kitchen, still holding the ax behind his back ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> We&#8217;ll have hot water soon.<br />
Woman: There&#8217;s wine. And I can make a risotto. ‚ãò‚ãô Do you think we&#8217;ll have hot water tonight?<br />
<b>Red:</b> By the time we finish dinner, it should be hot. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> This is superb. The rice is just right.<br />
Woman: Canned mushrooms. Best I could do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s excellent. You aren&#8217;t hungry.<br />
[ ELECTRICITY CRACKLES ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Who&#8217;s trying to kill you? Does it have something to do with what you told me before?<br />
Woman: I&#8217;m sorry?<br />
<b>Red:</b> You said you lost someone. Harsh words were spoken. Words you regret.<br />
Woman: I was out of my mind. There was no one. Just me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You don&#8217;t have to lie.<br />
Woman: Neither do you. You&#8217;re no hungrier than I am. You&#8217;re not enjoying a single bite of that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I told you this is&#8230;.<br />
Woman: Superb. The quality of the cooking is wholly irrelevant in this case, isn&#8217;t it? Given the circumstances.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And those are?<br />
Woman: You tell me. Tell yourself. Say it out loud.<br />
<b>Red:</b> [ Pause, then: ] It was a Hobson&#8217;s choice.* There was a woman and her child. Both were doomed. Both would die. I could either save one or lose both. I chose the child. It was&#8230; it was the worst thing I&#8217;ve ever had to do in my life. Worst thing by far.<br />
Woman: You didn&#8217;t have a choice.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s always a choice. I was arrogant. I presumed that there was an order to things, that there was&#8230; that if I nourished and protected and taught the child, she would be safe&#8230; &#8230;and happy.<br />
Woman: And she was neither.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No matter what I tried to do, all I brought her was misery and violence, and eventually&#8230;<br />
Woman: Death.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes.<br />
Woman: And now you&#8217;re dead. You believe there&#8217;s nothing left for you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It&#8217;s that obvious?<br />
Woman: Nothing about you is obvious. What brought you here?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I honestly don&#8217;t know.<br />
Woman: You&#8217;ve been here before.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Once, a long time ago. I was a very different person then. You?<br />
[ KNOCK ON DOOR ] [ DOOR BUZZES ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red opens the door ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> What can I do for you, Officer&#8230; Duncan?<br />
Officer Duncan: We got a call from a neighbor. He noticed lights inside.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, Yeah. I was afraid that might happen. That&#8217;s why the candles&#8230; didn&#8217;t want to alarm anyone.<br />
Duncan: I take it you&#8217;re not trespassing.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Oh, good God, no. Jack and Ida are old family friends. Offered the place for the weekend.<br />
Duncan: Mind showing some identification?<br />
<b>Red:</b> No, no, no. No problem. I&#8217;ll be right back.<br />
Duncan: If you don&#8217;t mind, I&#8217;d prefer waiting inside.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Of course. My mistake. Please, please. It&#8217;s a bit chilly out. Wait here. I&#8217;ll get my I.D.<br />
[ Red goes into another room and selects from a set of driver&#8217;s licenses under various names, then returns to the front room ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry you had to come all the way out here on such a cold night.<br />
[ The officer looks in the kitchen and sees the candles, food and wine from dinner ]<br />
Duncan: Didn&#8217;t mention you had a friend.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yeah. My wife, Abigail. She&#8217;s feeling a little under the weather.<br />
Duncan: Didn&#8217;t touch a bite, it looks like.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. I can go upstairs and wake her, if you&#8217;d like.<br />
Duncan: No. No, that&#8217;s okay. Everything appears in order. You said you&#8217;re a friend of Jack and Ida&#8217;s.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes, I said I <i>was </i> a friend. Poor Jack. Miss the hell out of that man.<br />
Duncan: Yeah, yeah. It&#8217;s a crying shame. Ida just hadn&#8217;t been able to keep the place up since he passed. Enjoy your stay, Mr. Donnelly.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Thank you, Officer.<br />
[ Officer leaves ]<br />
Woman: He knows.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t think so. He&#8217;d have to be very good at hiding it.  We&#8217;ll see. Water should be hot. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The woman is bathing. Red is seated on a couch some distance away ]<br />
Woman: [ SIGHS ] How did you know Jack was dead?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I didn&#8217;t say he was dead. I said I missed him.<br />
Woman: Still, why would you miss him?<br />
<b>Red:</b> State of the place. Hasn&#8217;t been maintained. A man wouldn&#8217;t let that happen if he was around.<br />
Woman: You said &#8220;Poor Jack&#8221;?<br />
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;Jack&#8217;s Shack.&#8221; He took pride in that. Decorated it, carved his name on it. It&#8217;s falling apart. I figured he was either sick or dead.<br />
Woman: Could have been Ida.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I went with Jack. Men don&#8217;t usually last as long as women.<br />
Woman: You sound like an actuary.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I am, in a way.<br />
Woman: Have you ever killed anyone?<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s an odd question.<br />
Woman: Have you?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes. Many. But never anyone who didn&#8217;t deserve it.<br />
Woman: Me, too.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I know.<br />
Woman: How?<br />
<b>Red:</b> There aren&#8217;t a lot of us. You learn to recognize it.<br />
Woman: Yes. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ GLASS SHATTERS ] [ Red looks for the perpetrator ]<br />
Woman: Behind you.<br />
[ GRUNTING ] [ Red and the man fight inside the bathroom ]<br />
Oh!<br />
[ GRUNTING ] [ Woman grabs the man from behind and slams his head against a mirror, then the sink ‚Äì several times. He collapses dead onto the bathroom floor ]<br />
[ Red coughs ]<br />
Woman: You all right?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yeah. Thank you. You know him?<br />
Woman: It doesn&#8217;t matter. He&#8217;s one of them. Not the first, not the last.<br />
[ They wrap the body in the plastic shower curtain and clean up the blood ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ The woman is playing √©tudes on the grand piano ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Why did you go into the water? What made you decide?<br />
Woman: You&#8217;ve never killed anyone who didn&#8217;t deserve it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes.<br />
Woman: That is a fine thing. A noble thing. But not terribly difficult.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s true.<br />
Woman: Have you ever spared someone who deserved to die?<br />
<b>Red:</b> There was a woman I loved. She was&#8230; my life. My heart. And she died. She left behind a little girl. One last, precious piece of herself. </p>
<blockquote><p>
[ Flashback ( or Flashforward ‚Ä¶ )]<br />
<b>Red:</b> She&#8217;ll need protection.<br />
Tom: Only if you&#8217;re in her life. Go. Stay away. I won&#8217;t let you make the same mistake with her&#8230; &#8230;that you made with Liz.
</p></blockquote>
<p><b>Red:</b> I would give anything to be a part of that child&#8217;s life, but a man made it clear I would never see her&#8230; hold her&#8230; watch her grow. And I knew in that moment, I would never be any part of that beautiful little girl&#8217;s life. Because&#8230;<br />
Woman: He was her father.<br />
<b>Red:</b> And to harm him would be to harm her. A mortal sin. Her mother is gone. The father is what she has left in the world.<br />
Woman: Her father.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes.<br />
[  CELLPHONE VIBRATES ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
Man: [ On cellphone ] Gregory, do you copy? Did you copy that?
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Woman  breaks the phone in half ]<br />
Woman: We don&#8217;t have much time. They&#8217;re coming. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> This&#8217;ll work. I&#8217;ll drive.<br />
[ Red loads the man&#8217;s body into back of a black SUV in the garage. The mysterious woman turns to walk away. Red grabs her arm ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m not leaving without you.<br />
Woman: Yes, you are.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. I&#8217;m not.<br />
Woman: Those men are after me. It&#8217;s my problem, not yours.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You made it my problem the moment you walked into the ocean.<br />
Woman: I didn&#8217;t ask for your help. Let me go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> No.<br />
Why not? What difference does it make to you?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Have you ever seen the aftermath of a suicide bombing&#8230;<br />
Woman: We&#8217;re wasting time.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I have. June 29, 2003. I was meeting two associates at the Marouche restaurant in Tel Aviv. As my car was pulling up, a 20-year-old Palestinian named Ghazi Safar entered the restaurant and detonated a vest wired with C4.<br />
Woman: Let me go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The shock wave knocked me flat, blew out my eardrums. I couldn&#8217;t hear. The smoke&#8230; It was like being underwater. I went inside. A nightmare. Blood. Parts of people. You could tell where Safar was standing when the vest blew. It was like a perfect circle of death. There was almost nothing left of the people closest to him. 17 dead, 46 injured. Blown to pieces. The closer they were to the bomber, the more horrific the effect.<br />
Woman: Stop.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That&#8217;s every suicide. Every single one. An act of terror perpetrated against everyone who&#8217;s ever known you&#8230; Everyone who&#8217;s ever loved you. The people closest to you&#8230; the ones who cherish you&#8230; are the ones who suffer the most pain, the most damage. Why would you do that?<br />
Woman: [ WHIMPERS ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Why would you do that to people who love you?<br />
Woman: I have no choice.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s always a choice.<br />
Woman: Is there? That little girl. The one you told me about? The one whose father you spared? What would you do if you knew&#8230; knew&#8230; that as long as you drew breath, as long as you continued to exist, her life would be in danger? She would be hunted, and she would be killed. What would you do?<br />
<b>Red:</b> What would <i>you</i> do?<br />
Woman: My child is being raised by someone else. I am her mother&#8230; and I am death to her. [ Tears ] So this is what I&#8217;m doing. I never wanted this.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I know.<br />
Woman: Then go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I can&#8217;t.  </p>
<p>[ Together, Red and Woman booby-trap the house. A bomb made from a propane tank. A live electric cable left in a sink with the water left to overflow. A mantrap made from cable and piano wire. Pounding music heightens the tension ]</p>
<p>[ VEHICLE APPROACHES ] [ There are six or seven men ]<br />
Woman: You still have time to go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I don&#8217;t know your name.<br />
Woman: Don&#8217;t be ridiculous, Raymond.  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Action sequence. In brief, the interlocutors are all dispatched, some by the booby traps. The woman pushes one man off a balcony. There is a brief gunfight. Red slashes one man&#8217;s throat. The woman stabs one man in the chest. One man is hung in the mantrap. ]<br />
[ AIR HISSING ] [ GROANS ] [ YELLS ] [ GRUNTS ] [ GRUNTS ] [ CHOKING ] [ GRUNTS ] [ ‚úõ All the while, suspenseful, pulsing music ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Woman: You okay?<br />
<b>Red:</b> We need to clean up and clear out.<br />
Woman: You get the car.<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s something wro&#8230; [ Red sees that the kitchen and other rooms are immaculate, untouched, as though he had just arrived. He goes to the staircase and shouts up: ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hello?<br />
[ Red climbs the stairs, searching for the woman ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Where are you?<br />
[ Red looks out the window. He sees the woman again walk into the ocean, exactly as before ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> No. No, no, no. [ Red runs down the stairs, out of the inn and across the beach. He looks at the surf pouring in. This time, the woman is nowhere to be seen ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ An old man has been using a metal detector to look for treasure under the sand. He is now digging for something ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Hey! Did you see a woman walk into the water?<br />
Treasure hunter: No. I didn&#8217;t see no woman.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You sure?<br />
Treasure hunter: Yeah. I&#8217;m sure. Mister, the only living soul I&#8217;ve seen on this stretch in over two weeks is just you.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Just me.<br />
Treasure hunter: Yep.<br />
[ Red recalls moments he had with the woman, but this time he speaks woman&#8217;s words ]</p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;Canned mushrooms. Best I could do.&#8221;<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> &#8220;Behind you.&#8221;<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Red plays √©tudes on the grand piano ]
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Returning to the present, Red queries the treasure hunter ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Just me.<br />
Treasure hunter: Yep. Just you.<br />
[ The treasure hunter finds a necklace buried in the sand ]<br />
Treasure hunter: Hello.<br />
[ Though it is almost completely encased in sand, Red recognizes the necklace ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Could I, please? Please. I want to buy it. [ Brings out a thick wad of bills ]<br />
Treasure hunter: Ain&#8217;t worth anywhere near that.<br />
<b>Red:</b> It is to me.<br />
Treasure hunter: Okay, then. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red goes to the water&#8217;s edge and lets a wave wash over the necklace ]<br />
[ Red reads aloud the Russian inscription on the back of the necklace: ] </p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Red:</b> To Katarina, love Papa.
</p></blockquote>
<p>[ Suddenly, the mysterious woman appears at Red&#8217;s side ]<br />
Woman: You had no choice. It was me or Masha.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry.<br />
Woman: Raymond, you did save me. Through her. It was the only way. You chose well.<br />
[ The woman reaches out and places her palm against Red&#8217;s cheek, stroking it ]<br />
Treasure hunter: Hey, Mister!<br />
[ Red turns around ]<br />
Treasure hunter: You okay? Seem a little lost.<br />
[ The mysterious woman is gone ]<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
<b>Red:</b> There&#8217;s someone I need to see. [ Red turns and walks away from the shore ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

Dom: You have no right to go through her things.<br />
(Grocery BAGS THUD)<br />
Dom: And that&#8217;s my coat!<br />
<b>Red:</b> I was just imagining young Katarina covered in glitter. As an adult, it&#8217;s easy to dismiss this stuff as girlish frivolity. You forget the wonder it creates, the light captured, secret wishes evoked. It renders even the darkest days sparkly. (BLOWS glitter into the AIR) Never underestimate the power of glitter.<br />
Dom: Stop it.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Stop what?<br />
Dom: Stop&#8230; torturing me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> That was never my intention.<br />
Dom: (EXHALES) Then what are you doing out here? These boxes are all I have&#8230; all I have left of my daughter.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry, Dom. I understand.<br />
Dom: No, you don&#8217;t. You don&#8217;t understand. You think because Masha&#8217;s dead, now you&#8230; you can understand me? (SIGHS) You can&#8230; you can share my misery?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I feel bereft, just like you.<br />
Dom: No, not just like me. She&#8217;s gone because of choices you made for both of them. First Katarina and then Masha. As far as I&#8217;m concerned, you killed my entire family! No, you&#8217;re not like me. (THUD) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: Nez Rowan? You&#8217;re sure it was her?<br />
Samar: I had a pretty good angle on her face as she cracked me with the butt of her weapon. ü§ï It&#8217;s her.<br />
Ressler: How is that even possible? We had her dead to rights for the armed robbery of a nuclear facility, conspiracy to kidnap, accessory to murder.<br />
Cooper: I personally signed the paperwork for her transfer to Fort Meade to await trial.<br />
Ressler: So why isn&#8217;t she rotting in a cell?<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;ll have Aram look into it.<br />
Samar: Aram is taking a personal day today. He&#8217;s not dealing with Liz&#8217;s death very well. (TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE)<br />
Cooper: He&#8217;s not alone. I&#8217;ll look into the Rowan situation myself.<br />
Ressler: Look, she&#8217;s definitely working with the same team of mercs who tried to abduct Keen. Rowan&#8217;s extraction team outside the hotel today&#8230; they wore the exact same equipment as they did.<br />
Cooper: Okay, well, let&#8217;s find out from Mr. Stalder why they&#8217;re after him and how he connects to Liz. (TELEPHONE RINGS) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Benjamin Stalder: I run the Energy Consortium Group. We advise governments and private sector clients on energy and economic business models. I recommend who gets billion-dollar contracts and who doesn&#8217;t.<br />
Samar: So&#8230; That&#8217;s why you travel with such a heavy security contingent.<br />
Stalder: Yeah. That&#8217;s right. I&#8217;ve received plenty of death threats over the years.<br />
Ressler: We&#8217;ll need any record you have of those, along with a complete client list.<br />
Stalder: Of course.<br />
Samar: Did anything unusual happen today, before the abduction?<br />
Stalder: No. (SIGHS) I never left the suite. I was working on my speech for the Global Financial Council.<br />
Ressler: Can you think of any reason why someone would want to stop that speech?<br />
Stalder: No. It was just a general state of the industry address.<br />
Ressler: Mr. Stalder, do you have any connection with Elizabeth Keen?<br />
Stalder: The fugitive. Right? Uh, no, only what I hear in the news. Whatever happened to her, anyway? </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is helping put groceries away ]<br />
(SIGHS) (BOTTLES CLINK)<br />
Dom: That&#8217;s not where the capers go.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dom&#8230;<br />
Dom: Move.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You still have family.<br />
Dom: Who? The baby? I won&#8217;t live long enough to see her out of nappies. If I&#8217;m allowed to see her at all. I had to make do with photographs of Masha. Did you even tell her about me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> I couldn&#8217;t. You know how complicated it was.<br />
Dom: There was nothing complicated about it. We had to back out of Masha&#8217;s life to keep her safe, after you made a colossal mess of everything. Only you couldn&#8217;t stay well enough away, could you? Now you&#8230; you come to my house with this sorry tale of loss, like you&#8217;re the only one affected by this. You&#8217;re the only one whose feelings matter. Well, guess what, Raymond? Masha was my granddaughter, and now she&#8217;s dead without even knowing I existed! (SIGHS) All my sacrifices shot to hell. I could&#8217;ve spent the last 30 years just being her grandfather&#8230; You selfish prick. (EXHALES DEEPLY)<br />
<b>Red:</b> She had your temper.<br />
Dom: (SCOFFS) I loved that girl enough to let her go, which is more than you can say.  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Stalder: Did my office send you what you wanted?<br />
Ressler: Yes. We have your client list. We&#8217;re running them down now.<br />
Samar: But we need to go over your abduction one more time.<br />
Stalder:  We&#8217;ve been over it six times. I can&#8217;t stay here. I have to fly to Dubai tonight.<br />
Ressler: Listen, Mr. Stalder, leaving now would be a huge mistake. You&#8217;re in immediate danger. Stalder: (SIGHS) My firm contracts with the best security teams that money can buy. Now that we&#8217;re aware of the threat, I am confident in their ability to keep me safe. Now I&#8217;m sorry, but I have to go. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: Do you know who had Nez Rowan released from military custody three days ago?<br />
Panabaker: Oh, honey, you&#8217;ve come to a goat&#8217;s house looking for wool. I warned you, Harold. Stand down.<br />
Cooper: You know who did it.<br />
Panabaker: Have you found Raymond Reddington?<br />
Cooper: Damn it, Cynthia. Nez Rowan was part of a shadow army that left directly to the death of Agent Keen. Rowan was the best lead we have. Who let her go free?<br />
Panabaker: (CLOSES FILE) I don&#8217;t know. It&#8217;s over my head. What I can tell you is that there are certain U.S. government missions. Covert. Dangerous. Necessary. And they require the expertise of an independent organization.<br />
Cooper: Don&#8217;t patronize me. Those people got one of my best agents killed, and you expect me to walk away. How can I justify that?<br />
Panabaker: I know full well you look the other way when you need to, because working with an international criminal enables you to bring good to the world.<br />
Cooper: I can&#8217;t look the other way. Not this time. They took someone that I love.<br />
Panabaker: Best thing you can do for all of us is locate Reddington and find a way to keep him on your team.  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(CELLPHONE BEEPS, DIALING) (CELLPHONE the VIBRATES)<br />
Tom: [ To infant: ] Hold on. Hold on. (Phone VIBRATES) Yeah.<br />
Cooper: You ready to roll in the mud?<br />
Tom: Thought you&#8217;d never ask. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram come to the door of Dom&#8217;s house ]<br />
(KNOCKING ON DOOR) (BIRDS CHIRPING) (DOOR CREAKS) (SINGSONG VOICE)<br />
Aram: Surprise.<br />
<b>Red:</b> (INHALES SLOWLY, CLICKS TEETH)<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dembe&#8230;<br />
Aram: Please don&#8217;t be mad at him. Dembe understood how important this is, and you weren&#8217;t answering his calls, or I-I never would have dropped by unannounced. It&#8217;s rude, and&#8230; I hate to be rude.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What do you want, Aram?<br />
Aram: You need to come back with me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Why?<br />
Aram: We&#8217;re not getting anywhere. In the investigation of&#8230; Agent Keen&#8217;s death. We could use your help.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Harold Cooper is a very capable leader. He&#8217;ll sort it out.<br />
Aram: It&#8217;s more than that. I can&#8217;t work. The Post Office, without Agent Keen&#8230; Without you&#8230; it&#8217;s just a government building.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m sorry you came all the way out here for nothing, Aram. I can&#8217;t help you. (DOOR CREAKS)<br />
Aram: No. You gave me a speech over an empty grave, about the foundational elements in our lives. &#8220;People who form the brick and mortar of who we are.&#8221; How, when they&#8217;re suddenly not there, we&#8230; we collapse into rubble. Now it was after Agent Keen was almost killed by the Cabal. But I saved her. You looked into that empty grave back then and said you&#8217;d be staring at her if it weren&#8217;t for me. Now I understand why you have collapsed into rubble. I do, and I&#8217;m truly sorry. But I&#8217;m here to collect on your debt. You owe me. So let&#8217;s go.<br />
(VOICE BREAKING)<br />
<b>Red:</b> To pay&#8230; m-my debt to you would require more than I possess. I&#8217;m not coming back.<br />
[ Red closes door ] (FOOTSTEPS DEPART)</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(RESSLER SPEAKS INDISTINCTLY) (TELEPHONE RINGS IN DISTANCE)<br />
Ressler: If Reddington&#8217;s not coming back for Keen, he&#8217;s not coming back, period.<br />
Samar: Okay, so what&#8217;s our next move? Aram, did you have any luck with those servers from the basement?<br />
Aram: I thought I&#8217;d be able to figure out where they routed their data, but I couldn&#8217;t find the end of the proxy chain.<br />
Ressler: Well, they have to be bouncing it off some kind of hidden servers around the Earth.<br />
Aram: Or hidden servers&#8230; over the Earth. I checked all the viable telecom satellites in GEO and LEO orbit, but I didn&#8217;t check the offline ones. (TYPING)<br />
Cooper: Offline satellites?<br />
Aram: Yeah, there are thousands of unused and decommissioned satellites circling our heads&#8230; space junk. It&#8217;s not enough that we litter the planet. Okay, the challenge is to figure out which ones they used.<br />
(TYPING CONTINUES)<br />
Cooper: Agent Mojtabai. Agent Mojtabai&#8230; (STOPS TYPING) Welcome back. (RESUMES TYPING) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(DOOR CREAKS) (DOOR CLOSES)<br />
[ Red enters. There&#8217;s a glass of buttermilk for him on the counter. He takes a mouthful (GROANS) and heads to the sink to spit it out ]<br />
Dom: Don&#8217;t you dare!<br />
<b>Red:</b> (SWALLOWS) Ugh.<br />
Dom: (CHUCKLES)<br />
<b>Red:</b> (EXHALES DEEPLY) How do you drink this stuff?<br />
Dom: We drank it with every meal on the farm when I was a boy. But we had cows, and we made our own. In the summers, we made buttermilk pops in the freezer. Kept us all from passing out.<br />
<b>Red:</b> So buttermilk reminds you of home.<br />
Dom: I overheard your conversation with the Arab boy.<br />
<b>Red:</b> He&#8217;s from Delaware. You won&#8217;t be troubled again with unexpected visitors. I know how you value your privacy.<br />
Dom: Why didn&#8217;t you go with him?<br />
<b>Red:</b> What would be the point? There&#8217;s nothing I could do that would really matter.<br />
Dom: Cry me a river. Hmm? What the hell are you really doing here? You&#8230; you gave me the news about Masha. What do you want from me?<br />
<b>Red:</b> A way forward. I can&#8217;t live for long with what I feel inside. I don&#8217;t see how anyone can.<br />
Dom: You said it, chum. Look around here. You call this living? (EXHALES SHARPLY) (VOICE BREAKS) After I lost my daughter&#8230; (BREATHING UNEVENLY) I crawled&#8230; crawled into the wilderness like a mortally wounded animal to get as far away from the pack as I could, to&#8230; to run out the clock. Run out the clock and die. And&#8230; If you came for a survival manual, you won&#8217;t find it here. But you&#8230; you&#8217;ve got one thing I haven&#8217;t had for a long time. You&#8217;ve got a reason&#8230; a reason to walk out that door. It sounds to me like there are honest people out there who are depending upon you to&#8230; (STAMMERS, LAUGHS) God help them. God help them. (LAUGHS)<br />
<b>Red:</b> Dom, you&#8217;ve always had a good reason to walk out the door.<br />
(BREATHES UNEVENLY) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: Okay, I think I&#8217;m getting somewhere.<br />
Ressler: So you found the needle in the haystack?<br />
Aram: I&#8217;m not looking for a needle. We need the whole haystack. (TAPS KEY) And if I&#8217;m right, it&#8217;s the Artax Network.<br />
Cooper: What is that?<br />
Aram: It&#8217;s an old telecom project to provide data coverage to every corner of the Earth through a network of 73 satellites. Anyway, the company went bankrupt and the project was abandoned.<br />
Samar: But the 73 satellites are still out there.<br />
Cooper: You think our target is using them?<br />
Ressler: Is there any way to confirm that the network&#8217;s still active?<br />
Aram: Well, I&#8217;ve just gained access to a relay station, and I am about to lock onto one of the satellites. If it&#8217;s in use, the data will be encrypted, but&#8230; we&#8217;ll know if it&#8217;s active. Okay. (EXHALES DEEPLY) Here we go. (BEEP)<br />
Cooper: They have control of the Artax satellite network.<br />
Samar: And they used it to kill Liz.<br />
Ressler: All right. Can we use it to find them?<br />
(TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE)<br />
Aram: Okay, so I was able to get a location by examining the latency patterns in the satellite signal. They&#8217;re being fed to 2054 Pulaski Avenue.</p>
<p>[ SWAT team rolls up to building ] (TIRES SCREECH)<br />
SWAT Leader: Concrete panels with granite faces. We&#8217;ve got no line-of-sight inside. Only one point of entry.<br />
Ressler: Then only one point of egress. Lock it up tight after we breach.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
Operator 4-6: HQ, this is Operator 4-6. We have poachers at the Eagle&#8217;s Nest. Initiating the protocol.<br />
(BEEP, SHREDDER WHIRRING) (MICROWAVE BEEPS) (MICROWAVE WHIRRING)<br />
Operator 4-6: They&#8217;re in. (POPPING) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Aram: Other than Nez, we can&#8217;t put faces to any of the mercs. So I scrubbed through the Warwick&#8217;s security footage to try and find some.<br />
Cooper: Good job. What&#8217;d you get us?<br />
Aram: (TAPS KEY) Nothing. Um, at least no mercs. But I did find this&#8230; (TAPS KEYS)<br />
Cooper: A shot of our victim. One hour before his abduction. Stalder told Ressler and Navabi he never left his suite. Was he lying or did he just forget?<br />
Aram: Well, that doesn&#8217;t look like a woman&#8230; or a conversation&#8230; he&#8217;d have forgotten. (TAPS KEY)<br />
Cooper: Who is she?<br />
Aram: I don&#8217;t know. And we can&#8217;t ask Stalder. I checked. He just cleared U.S. airspace. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(TELEPHONE RINGING IN DISTANCE)  (ZIPPER ZIPS, POPPING IN MICROWAVE)<br />
Operator 4-6: They&#8217;re onto the 11th floor. Go. 15 seconds and counting.<br />
[ The men clear out ]<br />
(BEEPING) ( üí•üî•üí• EXPLOSION üí•üî•üí•) (CRACKLING AND SIZZLING) (INDISTINCT SHOUTING) (CRACKLING CONTINUES)<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />
[ Ressler and the SWAT team come in to destroyed communications center ]<br />
Ressler: All right, do a full vertical sweep. They&#8217;re somewhere in this building.<br />
(CRACKLING CONTINUES)<br />
Samar: [ Looks in microwave ] So much for evidence.<br />
(CRACKLING)  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Red is working on a project in Dom&#8217;s garage ]<br />
(SANDING) (BLOWS AIR)  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Tom is at airport, secretly clicking photos of Cynthia Panabaker talking with a woman with long black hair ]<br />
(ENGINES WHIRRING) (CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING) (SPEAKING INAUDIBLY) (SHUTTER CLICKS) (SHUTTER CLICKS) </p>
<p>(DOOR OPENS, METRONOME TICKING) (DOOR CLOSES) (TICKING CONTINUES)<br />
Dom: Raymond?<br />
[ No answer, but: Red has fixed not only Dom&#8217;s metronome, but the damaged C-sharp key on the piano. Dom smiles broadly ]<br />
(TICKING CONTINUES) (TICKING CONTINUES) (CHUCKLES)<br />
Dom: Raymond! (PLAYS NOTE) (TICKING CONTINUES) [ Dom turns off the metronome ] (TICKING STOPS) (SIGHS) (Dom begins PLAYING SOMBER <a href="#piano">PIANO PIECE)</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ PIANO MUSIC CONTINUES ]<br />
[ Red visits Liz&#8217;s grave ]</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ PIANO MUSIC CONTINUES ]<br />
Cooper: Thank you for having dinner with me. It was nice.<br />
(SEAT BELT CLATTERS)<br />
Charlene: Mm-hmm. You&#8217;re welcome to come inside.<br />
Cooper: No. Not tonight, but maybe we can have dinner again. Tomorrow?<br />
Charlene: (WHISPERS) Yeah.<br />
(SWITCH CLICKS)<br />
(SIGHS DEEPLY) (CHUCKLES) (SWITCH CLICKS) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ PIANO MUSIC CONTINUES ]<br />
[ Samar is about to leave darkened Post Office. She noticed Ressler is in Liz&#8217;s office. She pauses, then departs. Ressler finds Liz&#8217;s wooden foot massager under her desk, smiles ] </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(Infant FUSSING) (Tom WHISPERS)<br />
Tom: Huh? Yeah, I know. (GASPS) Wait. Shh. (WHISPERING) It&#8217;s okay. Shh. (FUSSING CONTINUES) (GASPS) Shh. What did you say? Oh, come here. (FUSSES)<br />
[ Tom finally succeeds in swaddling the baby ]<br />
Tom: I did it. I did it, huh? I got you. I got you. We did it. Yeah, we did.  (EXHALES DEEPLY) </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
(Elevator DOOR CLANKS)<br />
Cooper: Tell me you found something useful.<br />
Tom: Depends. I followed Panabaker to the airport, where she had a meeting on the tarmac with this woman.<br />
Cooper: That&#8217;s the woman that Stalder met at the hotel just an hour before his attempted abduction.<br />
Tom: Who&#8217;s Stalder?<br />
Cooper: Benjamin Stalder. A high-powered executive at an energy consortium. Whoever was tracking Liz was also going after him.<br />
Tom: Why?<br />
Cooper: I don&#8217;t know. We let him go, but I&#8217;m getting the distinct feeling that was a mistake. Stalder&#8217;s obviously more involved than he was letting on.<br />
Tom: So who is this woman? [ The woman with the long black hair ]<br />
Cooper: We don&#8217;t know yet. The hotel photo wasn&#8217;t much to go on, but with these new images, Aram should be able to locate her in one of our databases.<br />
Tom: Liz was convinced that her mother was the one who tried to kidnap her. Reddington said she died years ago, but Liz didn&#8217;t believe that, and neither do I. I think we&#8217;re staring at Katarina Rostova.  </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Aram is at his computer at home ]<br />
(KNOCK ON DOOR) (DOOR CREAKS)<br />
Aram: Mr. Reddington.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m here to pay my debt to you, Aram.<br />
Aram: You&#8217;re back.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Strap on your bike helmet. We&#8217;re going to work. </p>

<blockquote><p>

<p>Aram: Mr. Reddington says her name is Susan Scott Hargrave.<br />

Aram: Or we could try and get the intel without her knowing. If one of you could get close enough to her, I think I can get what we need.<br />

<p>&nbsp;<br />
Cooper: The warrant was denied.<br />

Aram: Nowhere yet. We tried hacking her laptop, but she was on a highly encrypted network, so Tom started talking with her, and seriously, this guy should write a book. Anyway, we are implementing plan &#8220;B&#8221; tonight&#8230; on their date.<br />

Aram: Mr. Clark made three calls today to another secure cell. Now, we can&#8217;t trace the owner of that cell, but believe it or not, it is on right now, so I have been triangulating its location. They are somewhere on this block near Eighth and King. I&#8217;m still running algorithms, but I should be able to vector it down within a few hundred square feet.<br />
Cooper: Get there now. If we can&#8217;t get to Halcyon through the front door, we&#8217;ll have to kick down the back. </p>

<p>&nbsp;<br />

Scottie: I didn&#8217;t kill Masha. Elizabeth Keen, whatever you want to call her. She died in childbirth. Perhaps if she&#8217;d been in a proper hospital&#8230;<br />
[ üí• Red shoots Scottie in the arm ]<br />
Scottie: Aah! Damn you! Oh! I couldn&#8217;t foresee what happened to that poor girl any more than you. I told you I was hired to abduct her, not take her life.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Who hired you?<br />
Scottie: You know exactly who hired me.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;d like to be sure.<br />
Scottie: Alexander Kirk. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Ressler and Cooper are on the phone ]<br />
Ressler: Talked to the guard. He says that his partner jumped him from behind.<br />
Cooper: Why? To help Reddington?<br />
<b>Red:</b> More than likely the guard was in on the abduction, which Reddington walked right into despite knowing it was a trap.<br />
Cooper: I&#8217;m looking at a report that says the containers of oil we seized never made it into evidence. It seems the entire convoy was hijacked this morning.<br />
Ressler: You think Reddington took it?<br />
Cooper: Let&#8217;s just say I get the feeling he has an agenda here he&#8217;s not sharing with us. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<b>Red:</b> You know, I used to have such high hopes for your organization. High hopes for Howard. Halcyon was once such a promising company&#8230; like AOL. Put an entire generation online. Companies can so easily lose their way. Forget what it was that made them great to begin with. I remember a time when your husband never would have taken a job from a man like Alexander Kirk, if only out of respect for his friends.<br />
Scottie: Howard didn&#8217;t take that job. We haven&#8217;t had sex in four years. We&#8217;re rarely in the same country, let alone the same bed.<br />
<b>Red:</b> What bed have you been occupying?<br />
Scottie: I&#8217;ve been assuming a larger role in a management position lately.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You don&#8217;t say.<br />
Scottie: We&#8217;ve never been more successful. Listen, Red&#8230; I regret what happened to Elizabeth Keen. But her kidnapping was simply a business decision. You of all people should recognize that. We all do what we have to in order to survive. I know Howard and I do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Survival is all relative. There are limits, even for people like us. Especially for people like us.<br />
Scottie: When Kirk hired us to abduct Masha, he also wanted me to kill you. Sorry I didn&#8217;t take that job.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Here&#8217;s where we stand. Elizabeth Keen is dead, which means you are, too. Alexander Kirk is coming to kill you. The only surprise is that I got to you first.<br />
Scottie: You killed a lot of people trying to reach me. Well, here I am. Finish what you came to do.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You have it all wrong, dear. I didn&#8217;t come to kill you. I came here because you and I are about to climb into bed together, just for a quickie. We now share a mutual enemy. So, let&#8217;s get you bandaged up, not that you aren&#8217;t even lovelier with a little blood trickling down your arm. </p>

<h2>üî¥ Episode 3:22 Alexander Kirk</h2>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
NBC&#8217;s series <b>The Blacklist</b> starring <b>James Spader</b> and <b>Megan Boone</b><br />
<b>Series created by:</b> Jon <b>Bokenkamp</b><br />
Program air date: 5/12/2016 in the US<br />
Permalink: <a href="http://wp.me/pDKwi-2XE" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/pDKwi-2XE</a> ¬§ Storybook: <a href="http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#kirk" rel="nofollow">http://wp.me/PDKwi-1f3#kirk</a></p>
<blockquote><p>
<b>Blurb: </b>Enemies unite as Red, the FBI Blacklist Team and Scottie Hargrave&#8217;s forces move in on Alexander Kirk, the man ultimately responsible for Elizabeth Keen&#8217;s death. Tom is shocked when Red reveals a secret from the past.
</p></blockquote>

<p>&nbsp;<br />
(DOG BARKS) (INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS) (BUZZER)<br />
Karokaro: This is my Bitcoin wallet address. As soon as a transaction is confirmed, she&#8217;ll be released.<br />
Scottie: As you know, the American government refuses to negotiate with terrorists, which is why the Palmer family contracted my firm to negotiate on their behalf.<br />
Karokaro: What is this?<br />
Scottie: My Bitcoin wallet address.<br />
Karokaro: (CHUCKLES) You don&#8217;t pay the ransom, she dies.<br />
(GUN COCKS)<br />
Scottie: You and I both know Miss Palmer isn&#8217;t here, Karokaro. You know it because you never had any intention of giving her to me, and I know it because I&#8217;ve already set her free. Call your man at the port. You have a situation. An hour ago, a strike team raided your holding site at Muara Angke. They took Miss Palmer, along with the other eight workers you were holding, so the kidnapping part of the story&#8217;s over, which leaves us with the business at hand. You&#8217;re not ransoming me. I&#8217;m ransoming you. And the amount is $3 million, not $1 million. </p>
<p>(SPEAKS INDONESIAN) (DIALING) (SPEAKING INDONESIAN) </p>
<p>Scottie: I don&#8217;t know if it bothers you telling people things they don&#8217;t want to hear, but it makes me uncomfortable, which is ironic because most people think I&#8217;m a bully. They think I enjoy it, being blunt, making people feel small, but nothing could be further from the truth. Years ago, I-I suffered an unspeakable loss. And since then, I&#8217;ve been crippled by free-floating anxieties that attach to pretty much anything. Some days I-I can&#8217;t even get out of bed. I haven&#8217;t slept through the night in two years. 4:00 a.m., I&#8217;m up doing Sudoku. Normally, I-I delegate a meeting like this because, uh, conflict, it&#8217;s debilitating. But I&#8217;m working on the power of positive confrontation. </p>
<p>(SPEAKING INDONESIAN) (MAN SPEAKING INDONESIAN) </p>
<p>Scottie: I-I haven&#8217;t brushed up on my Indonesian in a while, but I&#8217;m going to guess he&#8217;s telling you your brother&#8217;s being held hostage by my people. True. If you want to see your brother alive again, you&#8217;re gonna transfer the money. </p>

Tom: I don&#8217;t want your money. I don&#8217;t want your protection. I want answers. The woman who killed Liz, you walked right into her trap after I warned you. What happened?<br />
<b>Red:</b> Alexander Kirk.<br />
Tom: I don&#8217;t know who that is.<br />
<b>Red:</b> The man who ordered the attack on your wedding. He&#8217;s ultimately responsible for Elizabeth&#8217;s death. I&#8217;m going to find him.<br />

Tom: I&#8217;m gonna help you find him.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Absolutely not.<br />
Tom: He&#8217;ll come for her, for Agnes.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Yes.<br />
Tom: I can&#8217;t stand by and watch that happen. You want me to accept your offer to help with Agnes, then you need to accept my help with this. So, tell me about Alexander Kirk. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
[ Scene shifts to the Post Office ]<br />
<b>Red:</b> Alexander Kirk is the alias of an oligarch who made a fortune after the fall of the Soviet Union buying mining operations for pennies on the dollar. In 2002, he went into hiding after falling out of favor with the Kremlin. He owes his survival to some of the world&#8217;s most powerful politicians whose careers he secretly bankrolls. But Alexander Kirk is the man responsible for Elizabeth&#8217;s death. He hired Susan Hargrave to abduct her, which is why we need to work with Hargrave to find him.<br />
Cooper: Work with her?<br />
Ressler: How about arrest her?<br />
Aram: This sounds like a bad idea.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Until it&#8217;s not. The aid workers who were abducted in Jakarta? Your government refused to pay the ransom, turned its back on three young people who were captured for doing nothing more than providing medical services to the poor. Today, they&#8217;re home because Susan Hargrave committed what your government considers to be a crime in order to get them back. She&#8217;s a brilliant strategist. And if we want to get Alexander Kirk, we&#8217;re going to need her help to do it. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Scottie: His finances are the way in.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Kirk&#8217;s holdings are out of reach. The Caymans, Zurich.<br />
Scottie: They were out of reach until Citizens United. Kirk has personally financed a 501(C)(4) super PAC in support of Senator Robert Diaz&#8217;s presidential bid.<br />
<b>Red:</b> How much?<br />
Scottie: lt&#8217;s hard to tell. It&#8217;s all dark money, but I believe it&#8217;s north of $300 million. Diaz is the front-runner. If he gets elected, Kirk&#8217;s reach will extend into the White House.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I&#8217;m impressed.<br />
Scottie: Like I care. If we steal Diaz&#8217;s money, Kirk won&#8217;t be far behind.<br />
<b>Red:</b> Him and everyone else.<br />
Scottie: It&#8217;s a presidential campaign. If that money goes missing, everyone on the planet will take notice.<br />
<b>Red:</b> You make it sound so fun.<br />
Scottie: What about the husband, Tom Keen?<br />
Scottie: He thinks I&#8217;m responsible for the death of his wife.<br />
<b>Red:</b> I think you&#8217;re responsible for her death. I&#8217;m looking past that because I want Alexander Kirk&#8217;s head. And so does Tom Keen. I must admit I&#8217;ve never liked you, Scottie. Looking at you makes my toes curl. But robbing the next President of the United States? This is gonna be a gas. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

Scottie: Rubber baby buggy bumpers. Rubber baby buggy bumpers. Rubber baby&#8230; My, what a dear, sweet child.<br />

Scottie: With a seven-figure donation that built this wing. (CHUCKLES) The grasp of these tiny fingers. I&#8217;d forgotten. I understand we&#8217;re gonna be working together to find the man who took Elizabeth from you.<br />
Tom: You took her from me.<br />
Scottie: No. Alexander Kirk did. He&#8217;s why I&#8217;m here, to tell you I&#8217;m putting the full resources of my company behind the effort to find Kirk and bring him to justice.<br />
Tom: Give me my little girl. She&#8217;s all I care about.<br />
Scottie: I remember my little one looking up at me, eyes full of wonder. They say losing a child is something one never recovers from. I hope you never experience that kind of loss.<br />
Tom: For the moment, we have a common enemy, so&#8230; I&#8217;ll work with you.<br />
Scottie: You have a lovely child. 10 minutes. I&#8217;ll send Solomon to pick you up. Got a lot of work to do.</p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Solomon: I hope you&#8217;re a chocoholic, my friend. We&#8217;re going to the chocolate factory.<br />
Tom: Let me say one thing. I&#8217;m not your friend. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />

Solomon: This is what happens when the government outsources 70% of its intelligence budget. You&#8217;re 150 feet below the largest privately owned tactical training center in the country, complete with R&amp;D labs, ship-boarding simulators, and two airfields. We do threat assessment, port security, and diplomatic training, and those are just the services that the public knows about&#8230; the black-and-white divisions. Then&#8230; there&#8217;s Grey Matters. (WHIRRING) Grey Matters handles the cases that are legally questionable, yet morally justifiable. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Nez: You&#8217;re late. She&#8217;s not happy.<br />
Solomon: Promise you won&#8217;t kick my ass. &#8216;Cause she could kick my ass.<br />
‚ãò‚ãô<br />

Ressler: Yeah, but they&#8217;re the same people who killed her.<br />
Cooper: You! Navabi!<br />
Tom: Hey. If I can do this, so can you.<br />
Scottie: Enough! We&#8217;re on the clock. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Alexander Kirk: (SPEAKING FRENCH) I don&#8217;t need your protection. After the U.S. election, approval will be a formality.<br />
Female aide: I just spoke to D.C. We have a confirmed location of the child.<br />
Kirk: I want this done today. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Scottie: The way to get Kirk&#8217;s attention is through his money, and the only money we can get to is sitting in Diaz&#8217;s war chest, which is unfortunate for the bloviating senator from Missouri because he cannot win the election without it, and we&#8217;re gonna steal it.<br />
Cooper:  The Bureau prevents bank robberies. We don&#8217;t commit them.<br />
Nez: Senator Diaz&#8217;s success in November rests on winning three key swing states. To do that, Futures America, a PAC financed by Alexander Kirk, intends to purchase over $300 million in TV ads from now until election day. The money is wired to media outlets via a secure terminal from a single account at Key Atlantic Bank in Manhattan. To get the money, we need to access the terminal from the server room. The good news is we can take the bank in under two minutes. The bad news is the second we walk in, any teller can trip a silent alarm that will lock down the area of the bank where the secure terminal is located. So we won&#8217;t be able to access it before the police arrive.<br />
Samar: That&#8217;s it? Your plan is awful.<br />
Tom: It&#8217;s brilliant. The robbery is a show. You want the police to arrive, followed by the FBI. The heist gets you in, gives you time to access the terminal&#8230;<br />
Ressler: We rob the bank while everyone else thinks that we are trying to find the robbers. Thanks, but no thanks.<br />
Scottie: You work with the single most sought-after criminal in America. Thanks to you, he&#8217;s not only free, his criminal empire&#8217;s expanding. You, all of you, have proven quite capable of parking your selective morality when the moment serves. I suggest finding Elizabeth Keen&#8217;s killer is just such a moment. It&#8217;s &#8220;badges in the drawer&#8221; time, people. This is a revenge movie. </p>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
Loan Officer: Mr. Loescher, we sent out a foreclosure letter three weeks ago.<br />
Zack Loescher: No, I have the paperwork in my car. Y-You never sent me a&#8230; Just hold on. I can show you. Sadie. Sadie, don&#8217;t move, okay? I&#8217;ll be right back.<br />

‚ãò‚ãô<br />

We had rented a house that summer, spent the whole week on the beach building sand castles with drawbridges and moats.That night, Howard and I had a&#8230; big fight. Too much to drink. Next morning, Christopher was gone. The police searched everywhere, but&#8230; nothing. He was just&#8230; gone. Like his castle. ‚ô™ I&#8217;m gonna get back to believing ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ It&#8217;s been a long, long time now ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ I&#8217;m gonna get up and make it look easy ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ Even though I don&#8217;t know how ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>Liz: My daughter, my husband&#8230; where are they? What have you done with them? </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I&#8217;m not gonna try and make it even ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>Kirk: Hello, Masha. </p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ I&#8217;m way behind by now ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>Kirk: I&#8217;ve been imagining this moment for the last 25 years.<br />
Liz: Who are you?<br />
Kirk: Alexander Kirk. That wasn&#8217;t always so. Once, a long time ago&#8230; my name was Constantin Rostov.‚ô§</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ Everyone thinks I dodged a bullet ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ But I think I shot the gun ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ And everyone thinks I dodged a bullet ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ But I think I shot the gun ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>Kirk/Rostov: Masha, I&#8217;m your father.‚ô§</p>
<blockquote><p>
‚ô™ And everyone thinks I dodged a bullet ‚ô™<br />
‚ô™ But I think I shot the gun ‚ô™
</p></blockquote>
<p>&nbsp;<br />
<a href="#top">‚¨Ü go to top</a><br />
